---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const b = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, "");
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Project Overview — TriCel CxnA | iDEC 2025"
  description="Full overview of the CxnA directed evolution project: bifunctional-to-trifunctional enzyme engineering and activity enhancement, affiliated with iDEC 2025."
>

  <!-- ═══ PAGE HERO ═══ -->
  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">Project Overview</p>
      <h1>Engineering CxnA toward trifunctionality</h1>
      <p>
        CxnA is a natural two-in-one cellulase. We are using directed evolution to try to add
        a third catalytic activity — and to improve the two it already has.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══ PLAIN LANGUAGE SUMMARY ═══ -->
  <section class="section section--alt" aria-labelledby="summary-heading">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <p class="eyebrow">In plain language</p>
        <h2 id="summary-heading">What are we actually doing?</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="summary-grid">
        <div class="prose">
          <p>
            Cellulose — the structural material in plant cell walls and one of the most abundant
            organic substances on Earth — is made of long chains of glucose molecules. Breaking
            those chains all the way down to glucose (usable for fermentation and biofuel production)
            requires three different types of enzyme working together.
          </p>
          <p>
            Most engineered systems express all three as separate proteins, which is inefficient.
            Separate enzymes floating in solution don't always find their substrate at the right time,
            and producing multiple proteins is more expensive than producing one.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>CxnA</strong> is an existing enzyme from the soil bacterium
            <em>Cellulomonas fimi</em> that already combines two of these activities in a single
            protein chain — an exoglucanase and an endoglucanase — making it naturally bifunctional.
            It was originally characterised by Duedu &amp; French at the University of Edinburgh in 2016.
            <a class="cite" href="#ref-duedu" aria-label="Reference 1: Duedu &amp; French 2016">[1]</a>
          </p>
          <p>
            This project asks: can we go further? Can we evolve CxnA to also perform the
            third activity — beta-glucosidase, the enzyme that converts the disaccharide cellobiose
            into two molecules of glucose — creating a fully <strong>trifunctional</strong> enzyme?
            And separately, can we use directed evolution to improve the two activities CxnA already
            has, making it an overall better cellulose-degrading enzyme?
          </p>
        </div>

        <aside class="summary-aside">
          <div class="card">
            <h3 class="aside-label">The three activities of cellulose degradation</h3>
            <ol class="activity-list">
              <li>
                <span class="activity-num">1</span>
                <div>
                  <strong>Exoglucanase</strong>
                  <p>Attacks crystalline cellulose from chain ends, releasing the disaccharide cellobiose.</p>
                  <span class="badge badge--confirmed">CxnA WT &mdash; confirmed</span>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <span class="activity-num">2</span>
                <div>
                  <strong>Endoglucanase</strong>
                  <p>Cleaves β-1,4 glycosidic bonds within the cellulose chain, creating new accessible chain ends.</p>
                  <span class="badge badge--confirmed">CxnA WT &mdash; confirmed</span>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <span class="activity-num">3</span>
                <div>
                  <strong>Beta-glucosidase</strong>
                  <p>Converts cellobiose into two glucose molecules. The final step to usable fuel.</p>
                  <span class="badge badge--progress">Project A target &mdash; evolving</span>
                </div>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>

      <!-- Expandable technical framing -->
      <details class="expand mt-8">
        <summary>Technical framing: domain architecture and mechanistic rationale</summary>
        <div class="expand-body prose-width">
          <p>
            CxnA contains two distinct glycoside hydrolase (GH) domains: a GH10 domain
            (bearing both Cex-type exoglucanase and CenA-type endoglucanase activities) and
            a GH1-fold domain that is currently catalytically inactive relative to
            beta-glucosidase function in the wild-type protein.
          </p>
          <p>
            GH1 family beta-glucosidases use a retaining double-displacement mechanism,
            with two conserved glutamate residues acting as the catalytic nucleophile
            and general acid/base. The structural analysis in this project
            (see <a href={`${b}/results#drylab-docking`}>Results — Dry Lab</a>) identifies
            candidate residues GLU350 and GLU404 as potential catalytic positions in the
            GH1-fold domain of CxnA, and characterises a steric barrier involving GLN87
            and TRP281 that may need to be overcome for cellobiose binding.
          </p>
          <p>
            There is no direct published precedent for evolving a GH10 scaffold to acquire
            GH1-type beta-glucosidase activity.
            <a class="cite" href="#ref-liu" aria-label="Reference 2: Liu et al. 2018">[2]</a>
            This project tests that gap. The honest prior expectation is low; the experimental
            and computational framing is designed to generate interpretable data regardless
            of whether the primary evolution succeeds.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══ PROJECT A vs B ═══ -->
  <section class="section" aria-labelledby="tracks-heading">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <p class="eyebrow">Two parallel research tracks</p>
        <h2 id="tracks-heading">Project A &amp; Project B</h2>
        <p>Both tracks run simultaneously with shared reagents and infrastructure.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="tracks-grid">
        <!-- Project A -->
        <div class="track-card track-card--a">
          <header class="track-header">
            <span class="track-label">Project A</span>
            <span class="badge badge--progress">In Progress</span>
          </header>
          <h3>Trifunctional evolution: adding a third activity</h3>
          <p class="track-goal"><strong>Goal:</strong> Evolve beta-glucosidase (GH1-type) activity into the GH1-fold domain of CxnA.</p>

          <div class="track-section">
            <h4>Strategy</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Error-prone PCR (epPCR) on the GH1-fold region of CxnA to generate a mutant library</li>
              <li>Selection by growth on cellobiose as the sole carbon source</li>
              <li>Screening of surviving colonies using the fluorogenic substrate 4-methylumbelliferyl-β-D-glucopyranoside (MUG)</li>
              <li>Computational guidance from AlphaFold3 docking to target the active-site region</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="track-section">
            <h4>Honest framing</h4>
            <p>
              No direct literature precedent exists for this specific evolutionary transition.
              The project is designed to generate interpretable data at every stage — including
              if evolution fails, characterising <em>why</em> is a result.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="track-section">
            <h4>Dry lab inputs</h4>
            <p>
              AlphaFold3 structure of the GH1 domain · Cellobiose docking poses ·
              PLIP interaction analysis identifying GLU350, GLU404 as candidate catalytic residues ·
              Steric barrier characterisation (GLN87/TRP281)
            </p>
            <a href={`${b}/results#drylab-gh1`} class="track-link">View dry-lab results for Project A →</a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Project B -->
        <div class="track-card track-card--b">
          <header class="track-header">
            <span class="track-label track-label--b">Project B</span>
            <span class="badge badge--progress">In Progress</span>
          </header>
          <h3>Activity enhancement: improving what CxnA already does</h3>
          <p class="track-goal"><strong>Goal:</strong> Improve the kinetics and/or thermostability of CxnA's existing exoglucanase and endoglucanase activities.</p>

          <div class="track-section">
            <h4>Strategy</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>epPCR across the full CxnA coding sequence (or targeted to the GH10 domain)</li>
              <li>CMC (carboxymethylcellulose) plate clearing assay for endoglucanase activity</li>
              <li>MUC (4-methylumbelliferyl-β-D-cellobioside) assay for exoglucanase activity</li>
              <li>Direct comparison of mutant activity to wild-type CxnA baseline</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="track-section">
            <h4>Rationale</h4>
            <p>
              Project B provides an interpretable positive control: we are evolving activity
              that demonstrably already exists. This ensures the selection and screening system
              is validated even if Project A yields no active mutants.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="track-section">
            <h4>Dry lab inputs</h4>
            <p>
              AlphaFold3 structure of GH10/Cex domain · Cellobiose and xylobiose docking ·
              PLIP interaction map of GLU127, GLU233 · Tight pose convergence in GH10 supporting
              high confidence in the binding geometry
            </p>
            <a href={`${b}/results#drylab-gh10`} class="track-link">View dry-lab results for Project B →</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══ WHY IT MATTERS ═══ -->
  <section class="section section--alt" aria-labelledby="context-heading">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <p class="eyebrow">Broader context</p>
        <h2 id="context-heading">Why does this matter?</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="context-grid">
        <div class="context-item">
          <div class="context-icon" aria-hidden="true">🌿</div>
          <h3>Biofuel production</h3>
          <p>
            Efficient cellulose degradation is a key bottleneck in second-generation biofuel
            production from agricultural waste, forestry residues, and dedicated energy crops.
            A self-contained trifunctional enzyme could reduce the enzyme loading required
            per unit of glucose produced.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="context-item">
          <div class="context-icon" aria-hidden="true">♻</div>
          <h3>Biomass recycling</h3>
          <p>
            Converting plant biomass to fermentable sugars has applications in waste
            valorisation, paper and textile industry bioprocessing, and soil carbon cycling.
            More efficient single-enzyme solutions lower the barrier to deployment.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="context-item">
          <div class="context-icon" aria-hidden="true">🤖</div>
          <h3>Testing AI-assisted protein engineering</h3>
          <p>
            This project explicitly examines where AlphaFold3 structural predictions and
            computational docking can responsibly guide directed evolution — and where they
            cannot substitute for real experimental data. The limitations are documented
            and discussed, not hidden.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══ iDEC AFFILIATION ═══ -->
  <section class="section" aria-labelledby="idec-heading">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="idec-section">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">Affiliation</p>
          <h2 id="idec-heading">iDEC — International Directed Evolution Competition</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>iDEC</strong> is the International Directed Evolution Competition — an annual
            student research competition focused on applying directed evolution to solve real
            biological problems. Teams design and execute original directed evolution experiments,
            with results judged on scientific rigour, innovation, and communication.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-4">
            This project is affiliated with and submitted to iDEC 2025. The complete research
            record — including all methods, raw data, lab notebook entries, and honest discussion
            of limitations — is published on this site as the official project record.
          </p>
          <a
            href="https://idec.io"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener"
            class="btn btn-idec mt-6"
          >
            Visit the iDEC website
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="13" height="13" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M18 13v6a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H5a2 2 0 0 1-2-2V8a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h6"/><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"/><line x1="10" y1="14" x2="21" y2="3"/></svg>
          </a>
        </div>
        <div class="idec-logo-box" aria-hidden="true">
          <div class="idec-placeholder-logo">
            <span>iDEC</span>
            <span class="idec-placeholder-sub">2025</span>
          </div>
          <p class="idec-logo-caption">iDEC logo/badge — add official asset here</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══ REFERENCES ═══ -->
  <section class="section section--alt" aria-labelledby="refs-heading">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 id="refs-heading" style="margin-bottom:var(--sp-6)">References cited on this page</h2>
      <ol class="ref-list">
        <li id="ref-duedu">
          Duedu, K.O. &amp; French, C.E. (2016). Characterization of a bifunctional cellulase
          CxnA from <em>Cellulomonas fimi</em>. <em>Enzyme and Microbial Technology</em>.
          University of Edinburgh.
        </li>
        <li id="ref-liu">
          Liu, G. et al. (2018). Functional and structural characterization of a GH1 family
          beta-glucosidase. <em>Biotechnology for Biofuels</em>.
        </li>
      </ol>
      <p class="mt-4" style="font-size:0.85rem;color:var(--c-text-muted)">
        Full bibliography with all project references: <a href={`${b}/results#references`}>Results &mdash; References</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>

<style>
  /* ─── Summary grid ───────────────────────────────────────────── */
  .summary-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 3fr 2fr;
    gap: var(--sp-10);
    align-items: start;
  }
  @media (max-width: 800px) { .summary-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }

  .prose-width { max-width: var(--max-w-prose); }

  .aside-label {
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--c-text-muted);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    margin-bottom: var(--sp-4);
  }
  .activity-list {
    list-style: none;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--sp-5);
  }
  .activity-list li {
    display: flex;
    gap: var(--sp-3);
    align-items: flex-start;
  }
  .activity-num {
    width: 28px;
    height: 28px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background: var(--c-primary);
    color: #fff;
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    flex-shrink: 0;
    margin-top: 2px;
  }
  .activity-list p { font-size: 0.88rem; color: var(--c-text-muted); margin-top: var(--sp-1); max-width: none; }
  .activity-list .badge { margin-top: var(--sp-2); }

  /* ─── Tracks ─────────────────────────────────────────────────── */
  .tracks-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: var(--sp-6);
  }
  @media (max-width: 800px) { .tracks-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }

  .track-card {
    background: var(--c-surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--c-border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-xl);
    padding: var(--sp-6);
    border-top: 4px solid var(--c-primary);
  }
  .track-card--b { border-top-color: var(--c-accent); }
  .track-header {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: space-between;
    margin-bottom: var(--sp-4);
  }
  .track-label {
    font-size: 0.72rem;
    font-weight: 800;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--c-primary);
    background: var(--c-primary-light);
    border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
    padding: 0.2em 0.6em;
  }
  .track-label--b { color: var(--c-accent); background: var(--c-accent-light); }
  .track-card h3 { font-size: 1.1rem; color: var(--c-secondary); margin-bottom: var(--sp-3); }
  .track-goal { font-size: 0.95rem; color: var(--c-text); }
  .track-section { margin-top: var(--sp-5); }
  .track-section h4 {
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--c-text-muted);
    margin-bottom: var(--sp-2);
  }
  .track-section ul {
    padding-left: var(--sp-5);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--sp-2);
  }
  .track-section li { font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--c-text); }
  .track-section p { font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--c-text-muted); max-width: none; }
  .track-link {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-top: var(--sp-3);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--c-primary);
  }

  /* ─── Context ────────────────────────────────────────────────── */
  .context-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(240px, 1fr));
    gap: var(--sp-6);
  }
  .context-item {
    background: var(--c-surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--c-border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
    padding: var(--sp-6);
  }
  .context-icon { font-size: 2rem; margin-bottom: var(--sp-3); }
  .context-item h3 { color: var(--c-secondary); margin-bottom: var(--sp-2); }
  .context-item p { font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--c-text-muted); }

  /* ─── iDEC section ───────────────────────────────────────────── */
  .idec-section {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr auto;
    gap: var(--sp-10);
    align-items: start;
  }
  @media (max-width: 640px) { .idec-section { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }
  .btn-idec {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: var(--sp-2);
    padding: var(--sp-3) var(--sp-5);
    background: var(--c-primary);
    color: #fff;
    border-radius: var(--radius-md);
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: 0.92rem;
    transition: background 0.18s;
  }
  .btn-idec:hover { background: var(--c-primary-hover); text-decoration: none; }
  .idec-logo-box {
    text-align: center;
    min-width: 140px;
  }
  .idec-placeholder-logo {
    width: 120px;
    height: 120px;
    border-radius: var(--radius-xl);
    background: var(--c-surface-2);
    border: 2px dashed var(--c-border);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    font-weight: 800;
    font-size: 1.4rem;
    color: var(--c-text-faint);
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
  .idec-placeholder-sub { font-size: 0.8rem; font-weight: 600; opacity: 0.6; }
  .idec-logo-caption { font-size: 0.72rem; color: var(--c-text-faint); margin-top: var(--sp-2); }
</style>
